metadata.name: Castles #76
metadata.description:
I made 1B pixel art for the first time and I had a lot of fun doing it. Generally the majority of my fxHash drawings were PFPs, which I wanted to change it as well. You can also use Castles as phone backgrounds. Oh also there is no rarity in it, every drawing has same weight.

For screen shot, open it Castles in new tab via fxHash button. And press("S") to take (1152x2048) screen shot.

metadata.name: Copenhagen Interpretation #116
metadata.description:
The Copenhagen Interpretation of quantum physics suggests that objects don't have physical properties until being observed.

In this generative piece by itsgalo and Spøgelsesmaskinen, a set of objects are being held in "superposition" and finally positioned when observed and minted.

Use mouse/touch to zoom, pan, and rotate. Press 's' to grab a screenshot. Best viewed in Firefox.

metadata.name: "Gradient Framework" #62
metadata.description: "Gradient Framework" is my first ever minted NFT. It is an abstract exploration of color, composition, and texture.

metadata.name: Syzers #498
metadata.description:
Syzers is a generative synthesizer project with sounds altered by Tone JS.

···· On Tuesday, May 17, unsold editions will be burned ····

Visually it consists of 16 layers, in which more than 350 elements are combined randomly, generating synthesizers with unique environments and landscapes.
As for the sound, 40 tracks were recorded with analog synthesizers that were then assigned to each of the modules. These, combined in groups of 4, provide thousands of possible combinations. 
In addition, these sounds will be further modified by code effects that will randomly vary their properties.

Click to listen to the sounds

Many thanks to @Jpupper and @Fipiaggio for help with programming the sound part and @Purespider for the template. 
"FXHASH PFP Token Generator" https://github.com/PureSpider/fxhash-pfp

for best resolution "open live" then use the "download image" button on the lower right corner ;)

metadata.description:
In this piece, special attention is paid to negative space, which is emphasized by simple / bold color palettes.

metadata.name: Subdivisions #173
metadata.description:
As an artist with a background in engineering, I have always been a fan of technical drawings.
Architectural sketches and renderings fascinate me with their ability to visualize the conceptual.

I create generative art for the same reason - to reveal the beauty in an algorithm.

This project represents the division of space using techniques that, for me, call to mind sitting
at a drafting table, straight edge in hand, imagining what might be possible.

You can export a high resolution PNG (5000x5000) by pressing the 'e' key.

Twitter: @jeffpalmer
https://jpalmer.dev

metadata.name: Mur #57
metadata.description:
Mur is a series of computational drawings of stacked and falling bricks. The bricks are placed in different configurations of walls, towers, stacks and paths, and are then exposed to gravity. 

The graphics are coded with p5.js and the rigid body simulations with ammo.js. In live mode, press 's' to save a screenshot and 'e' to save a high resolution image. Press 't' to toggle textures. 

Each scene is drawn twice, first brick by brick as they fall or stay in place, then the scene as a whole. Mur is optimized for Chrome, uses WebGL and may not work in all browsers.

metadata.name: (kinder)Garden, Monuments #197
metadata.description:
When Yazid and Zancan started their fxcollab journey, they knew very little about each other. They learnt about their rich cultural differences, their complementary graphic styles, and a 7-hour timezone difference. What they did have in common was each had two kids about the same age (one a pair of girls, the other boys).

Every kid was born a builder; every kid likes to sit in nature. It’s their way of discovering the world and dreaming of their future accomplishments. While they marvel at the heights of the cities and monuments they construct out of stacks of cubes, parents marvel at their ability to elaborate an unlimited range of worlds out of a limited range of materials. 

This project celebrates the humble and versatile cube. A deceptively simple yet powerful object of play and learning, regardless of age, whether you’re stacking them up in a sandbox, or learning 3D graphics for the first time. 

This project is dedicated to kids, those who were once children, to the dreamers and builders who still enjoy playing with cubes.

Coded in Vanilla JS, the project combines Yazid's iconic “Hashed/Hatched” aesthetic incorporated into childhood wooden toy block structures, and Zancan's signature lush foliage and framework, which enables all iterations to be plottable.
 
Controls (in live view):
- Press [s] to get a SVG file suited for plotters
- Click on the image to download a 4K resolution PNG

metadata.name: RGB Elementary Cellular Automaton #844
metadata.description:
Stephen Wolfram's Elementary Cellular Automaton where 3 different rules are drawn in the Red, Green and Blue color components of the image.

Rules are selected randomly among a pre-selection of 53 rules from which nice behaviors emerge.

Tokens can have a cell size in the [1; 20] range.

metadata.name: #symmetriClew #45
metadata.description:
Thank you for adding me to your collection. Now that I’m a part of your tez fam, please open me in live view, enter ‘9’ or ‘10’, wait, press ‘P’, print me, put me on your wall, and enjoy.

#symmetriClew is a special collection inspired by, and in honor of, Clew #205.  Clew #205 is the only symmetrical #lostNotLost output in the 567-piece Clew collection.   A brief write up on #symmetriClew can be found at https://abstractment.art/symmetriclew.

Similar to Clew, this collection is designed for your wall.

When opening live view, you’ll be prompted to choose a render quality (1 for lowest; 10 for highest). The higher quality renders are for printing and zooming in to choose your own sub-composition or explore the details. Higher quality images will naturally take longer to render but will be worth the wait, especially if seeking to print. If you find a partial render particularly nice, you can press spacebar to pause (and unpause). Save a PNG by pressing ‘P’ or a JPEG with ‘J’. Medium and high quality renders are optimized for Chrome desktop and may not function on other browsers or mobile devices.

Thumbnail previews will render at lower quality.  Please keep in mind that I’m best enjoyed in live view.

created using p5js

#symmetriClew
abstractment, 2022

metadata.name: Zometric #155
metadata.description:
A journey into geometric shapes.
Real art is not hidden behind complicated and obscure forms. In this collection, we have tried to achieve a unique visual clarity by using the basic visual elements. A pure mixture between piet mondrian and paul klee. A combination of visual language of classical and modern art movements. Over 15 000 combination can be generated.
Made in p5.js

metadata.name: Unsolicited abstraction of modern times #164
metadata.description:
This piece is an abstraction and a reflection on the last era, on all that we have built and become. Are we proud of it or has it just been the result of iterating through the days? Since the technology boom, we have experienced great improvements, but perhaps also massive ...mistakes?  

Inspired by textbooks of the 80s, with elements that remind us of industry, technology, networks and systems, "Unsolicited abstraction of modern times" invites us to question our work to date. Has everything really changed?

unknowable 2022




Usage:
press [s] - save pixels (png)
press [p] - save vectors (svg)
